SIMPLE: siskin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Siskin
<hw>Sis"kin</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dan.
<ets>sisgen</ets>; cf. Sw. <ets>siska</ets>, G. <ets>zeisig</ets>, D.
<ets>sijsje</ets>; of Slav. origin; cf. Pol.
<ets>czy⟦zdot⟧</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A
small green and yellow European finch (<spn>Spinus spinus</spn>, or
<spn>Carduelis spinus</spn>); -- called also
<altname>aberdevine</altname>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The American
pinefinch (<spn>Spinus pinus</spn>); -- called also <altname>pine
siskin</altname>. See <er>Pinefinch</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name is applied also to several other related
species found in Asia and South America.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Siskin green</b></col>, <cd>a delicate shade of yellowish
green, as in the mineral torbernite.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Siskiwit</ent>⟦br⟧
